@endnode
@node ADDTAGS "Add Tags"
Command: Add Tags

   Pressing `A' will allow you to ADD a tagline to a specified listing.
It should be noted, however, that your tagline will not be added to the
listing immediately, but will hopefully be added the next time this
system's auto- maintenance runs.  If the tagline does not already exist
in the specified list, then it will be added, else it will be discarded.
@endnode
@node ADOPTLISTS "Adopt New Tagline Lists"
Command: Adopt New Tagline Lists

   Use ADOPT to add taglists that have INDEX files made for them already
into your TagLines file.  This is helpful if you find other SysOps using
taglists which you may NOT have on your system. By obtaining BOTH the data
and index files, this command allows you to quickly add the listing to
your setup, without having to go through the steps involved in scanning.
@endnode
@node CHOSENLISTS "Working With Chosen Lists of Taglines"
Command: Chosen Lists

   SuperTags allows the user to select taglines from specific lists. Each
of these lists contain taglines which generally have something in common
with each other.  For instance, they might each have to do with SysOps or
Men or Computers or Star Trek, etc.

   Some of these lists may be of interest to you, while others may not. It
is for this reason that this option exists.  Your "chosen" list is the
list of tagline libraries that YOU, SPECIFICALLY happen to like. After
creating this list, you can use one of the "Chosen List" methods discussed
under METHODS to tell the program to ONLY choose a tagline from one of
these specified lists.

   Refer to the @{"GENERAL" link GENERAL} item for information concerning selecting multiple
lists to add to your Chosen List.

   Refer to the @{"DELETE" link DELETELISTS} item for information concerning deleting list(s)
from your chosen listing.
@endnode
@node CHOSENTAGS "Chosen Tags"
Command: Chosen Tags

   Something you'll notice almost immediately is that there are MANY,
MANY taglines to choose from.  This may be TOO MANY for your liking. Even
though there may be a list you specifically like, that list may contain
many tags which you do not like.  It is for this reason that this option
is included.

   You can specify up to 20 taglines to place in your own, private,
tagline library. These taglines can come from any of the included tag
lists, or you can specify to create them yourself.  You'll have to then
choose one of the "Chosen Tags" methods discussed under METHODS to tell
the program to ONLY choose a tagline from this SPECIFIC listing.

   Refer to the @{"GENERAL" link GENERAL} item for information concerning selecting multiple
taglines to add to your Chosen List.

   Refer to the @{"DELETE" link DELETELISTS} item for information concerning deleting tag(s)
from your chosen listing.
@endnode
@node DELETECHOSEN "Delete from Chosen Lists"
Chosen: Delete from Chosen Lists

   Pressing `D' will allow you to delete an item from one of your Chosen
Lists. You'll be asked if you wish to delete a Chosen List or a Chosen
Tag.

   See the @{"GENERAL" link GENERAL} item for more information concerning selecting multiple
lists/tags to delete.
@endnode
@node GENERAL "General Information"
Command: General Information

   In addition to the visible commands, there are numerous other commands
and command aliases you can use, while inside SuperTags Config:

   At most prompts that ask you to select an item, you can use CNet Ranges
to select multiple items. For instance, typing:   1-5,8-11,23   would
allow you to specify items 1 thru 5, 8 thru 11 and 23.  Using these CNet
Ranges allows you to make rapid selections quickly and easily.  For more
help using CNet Ranges, exit SuperTags Config, then type @{"HELP RANGES" link RANGES} from
any CNet Command Prompt.

   In case you didn't already know this, you're SysOp should have made the
TAGS command available from any prompt on the system. This TAGS command
will load this config program and allow you to edit your tagline settings
anytime you think you need to. (I mention this in case you were placed in
the Config program, because it was your first time using the SuperTags.
Now you'll know how to get BACK into it when you need to!)

   If you have any problems using this program, or you are unsure on what
a particular function does, please do not hesitate to ask your SysOp. If
it's not something they feel comfortable answering, they'll then be able
to get in contact with the author, who SHOULD be able to find an answer.
@endnode
@node LISTLISTS "List Chosen Lists"
Command: List Chosen Lists

   Whenever you choose more lists for your Chosen Listing than can be
displayed on one line of the Config screen, you'll be able to press `L'
to view all your Chosen Lists.
@endnode
@node LISTTAGS "List Chosen Tags"
Command: List Chosen Tags

   If you have more than one tagline in your Chosen Tags listing(as you
no doubt will), you'll be able to use the `T' command to view these chosen
tags.
@endnode
@node SCANDIR "Scan Directory for New Tagline Lists"
Command: Scan Directory for New Tagline Lists

   There are two forms of SCANNING available. You can choose to either
scan for lists that do NOT have accompanying index files, or else you can
opt to scan ALL the listings again(in case you wish to update index files).

   During the scanning process, numerous things will occur:

      - The data file will be alphabetized.
      - It will then be passed through a duplicate checking routine.
      - After this, the index file will be calculated and created.
      - The index file, and updated data file, will both be saved to disk.

   If multiple files are found in the directory, this operation could take
some time, however you needn't stay and wait for it, as it will do all the
grunt work for you.

   Upon completion of the scanning process, you'll be asked if you wish
to automatically go to the Global Editing screen where you'll be able to
change specific settings for numerous listings of taglines quickly and
easily.
@endnode
@node SIGNATURES "CNet Signatures & Taglines"
Command: CNet Signatures & Taglines

   CNet Amiga BBS's have the ability to allow you to create "Signature"
files.  These are short text files where you can include information such
as your Real Name, Handle, BBS Information, etc. Whatever you'd like to
tell other people about yourself.  You usually use the `EP' command to
edit these signature files.

   This option allows you to tell the program how you wish to use these
signature files, in conjunction with the taglines.  There are presently
five different ways you can set this option:

   Place No Signatures with Taglines.

      - Using this setting will SUPPRESS, or skip, the printing of the
        signature file from text messages created by you.

   Place CNet's Default Signatures BEFORE Taglines.

      - This setting will tell the program to append your signature file
        to the text message, THEN append the tagline text.

   Place CNet's Default Signatures AFTER Taglines.

      - This setting will tell the program to append the tagline to the
        text message, THEN append your signature file.

   Place CNet's `Handle/Real Name' Default BEFORE taglines.

      - This setting will simply insert your handle(or real name) to the
        text message, THEN append the tagline. What exact info is appended
        to the message will depend on how your SysOp has the base you
        posted/replied in set up. [This option is NOT used when writing
        personal mail or feedback to the SysOp].

   Place CNet's `Handle/Real Name' Default AFTER taglines.

      - This setting will append the tagline to the text message, then
        simply insert your handle(or real name) after the tagline. The
        exact info printed will depend on how your SysOp has the base you
        posted/replied in set up. [This option is NOT used when writing
        personal mail or feedback to the SysOp].
@endnode
@node AMAINT "Run SuperTags MutoMaintenance Module"
Command: Run SuperTags AutoMaintenance Module

   This command simply allows you to launch the AMAINT module, without
having to wait for your CNet AutoMaintenance event to do it.  This comes
in handy when you(the SysOp) manually adds taglines to various listings.
@endnode
@node CENTERING "Centering Types"
Command: Centering Types

   There are numerous ways you may wish your tagline centered(and
justified) on the screen. Presently, there are seven different settings
for this option:

   - Use Random Border, With Tagline Randomly Justified.

        This option will randomly select one of the following six options.

   - Full Sized Border, With Tagline Left Justified.

SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ---------------------------------------------------.
| This is an example tagline!                                            |
`------------------------------------------------------------------------'

   - Full Sized Border, With Tagline Right Justified.

SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ---------------------------------------------------.
|                                            This is an example tagline! |
`------------------------------------------------------------------------'

   - Full Sized Border, With Tagline Center Justified.

SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ---------------------------------------------------.
|                       This is an example tagline!                      |
`------------------------------------------------------------------------'

   - Custom Sized Border, Left Justified On Screen.

SuperTags 2.53 Chosen --------.
| This is an example tagline! |
`-----------------------------'

   - Custom Sized Border, Right Justified On Screen.

                                           SuperTags 2.53 Chosen --------.
                                           | This is an example tagline! |
                                           `-----------------------------'

   - Custom Sized Border, Center Justified On Screen.

                      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen --------.
                      | This is an example tagline! |
                      `-----------------------------'

   In the examples shown above, the 3-Line Format is being depicted,
however you also have the option of creating a 1 or 2-Line format as well.
See the @{"FORMATS" link FORMATS} item for more information.
@endnode
@node COLORS "Change Colors"
Command: Change Colors

   Pressing `C' will allow you to select which colors will be used when
creating the tagline and border. These colors will only be visible in
areas of the bbs that allow them to be used. You can select foreground
and background colors for the `SuperTags 2.53 xxx' text, the border and
the tagline text.
@endnode
@node CONFIG "Edit SuperTags Config Values"
Command: Edit SuperTags Config Values

   The CONFIG EDITOR allows you to change the following settings, located
in the "SuperTags.cfg" file:

      - Should QuickTags be Used?
      - If QuickTags Are Mandatory, Which List Should Be Used?
      - Path to SuperTags Command Files.
      - Path to SuperTags TagList Files.
      - Tagline method to give to FIRST-Time users of SuperTags.
      - Default Menu Choices for Menu's 1 thru 5 on the CONFIG Screen.
      - Default settings to use on the GLOBAL EDITING screen during uses
        of the "Scanning Directory" operation.
      - All known AreaFix Passwords.
      - Ability to translate MORPH Codes when displaying long listings.
      - Ability to "temporarily" disable SuperTags for ALL users.
      - Lowest Group to consider a "Fellow SysOp", for use with the GRAB
        command to include INDEX(.ndx) files in archives.
      - Ability to suppress printing of "disabled" text messages.
      - select Only the Quotable Tags(those taglines less than 70
        characters in length)
      - Use QuickTags Module, instead of SuperTags Module.
      - Ability to specify taglist to use when in QuickTags mode.
      - SuperTags Title Text Default Setting. (0=No Text, 1=Both Texts,
        2=Just Title, 3=Just Name, 4=Ask the User)
@endnode
@node DELETELISTS "Delete Tagline Listings"
Command: Delete Tagline Listings

   In the event you ever decide you no longer wish to offer one or more
listings of taglines, you can choose to DELETE them.  You use CNet Ranges
to select the listings you wish to delete.  You'll then be asked if you
also wish to delete the physical files from your disk drive.

   Stating NO to this question will simply delete the list's entry from
your TagLines file, while SAVING the files on your disk drive(in case you
wish to add them in again sometime in the future).
@endnode
@node EDITLISTS "Edit Tagline List"
Command: Edit Tagline List

   You may wish to EDIT a listings settings, which is what this option is
used for.  You can choose to edit any of the following:

        - List's Filename.
        - List's Descriptive (Long) Name.
        - Minimum Access Group.
        - Which Genders May Use.
        - minimum AGE May Use.
        - May MCI's Be Used?

   You also have the ability to QUIT without editing anything.
@endnode
@node USER "Check USER Config Validity"
Command: User

   Pressing "U" will allow a SysOp to check the validity of a users 
SuperTags Config File(even their own). They'll be shown all available 
info pertaining to that user's current SuperTags settings. A check will 
then be performed for nine distinct errors which may appear in the user's 
config.

   The SysOp can then use the L, T, and/or E commands to respectively view 
the user's Chosen Lists, Chosen Tags, or Config Errors, if available.

   The following nine Config Errors are currently checked for:

         Random Chosen Lists Selected, but NO Chosen Lists on File!
          Random Chosen Tags Selected, but NO Chosen Tags on File!
       List Name Chosen, but Foreground & Background Colors are SAME!
         Border Chosen, but Foreground & Background Colors are SAME!
        The Tagline's Foreground and Background Colors are IDENTICAL!
       Signatures Chosen, but their Default Signature File Not Found!
     Signatures Chosen, but their Fido Handle Signature File Not Found!
    Signatures Chosen, but their Fido Real Name Signature File Not Found!
      User has ALL Message Text Types Disabled, but SuperTags Enabled!
@endnode
@node EDITTAGS "Edit Chosen Tags"
Command: Edit Chosen Tags

   Pressing the `E' key will allow you to EDIT any of the taglines in your
Chosen Tag listing.

   It is possible to add MCI-Color codes to Chosen Tags, even if they came
from lists that forbid their use, because these taglines now make up a
custom list which is only available to you.
@endnode
@node FORMATS "Tagline Line Formats"
Command: Tagline Line Formats

   The `Line Format' option allows you to choose the text layout mode you
wish to use for your taglines. There are presently four options:

    - Use Random Line Format.

        This option will randomly select one of the following 3 options.

    - Formatted for ONE Line.

        STags2.53: This is an example tagline!

    - Formatted for TWO Lines.

        This is an example tagline!
        ----- SuperTags 2.53 ------

    - Formatted for THREE Lines.

        SuperTags 2.53 Chosen --------.
        | This is an example tagline! |
        `-----------------------------'

   How long the lower line in the 2-Line format can be, as well as the
size of the border in the 3-Line format will depend on your centering
setting. Refer to the @{"CENTERING" link CENTERING} item for more information.
@endnode
@node GLOBALEDIT "Global Tagline List Editor"
Command: Global Tagline List Editor

   Sometimes, you may find the need to edit one or more settings for MANY
listings of taglines. Using the GLOBAL EDIT feature, you can make changes
to all listing settings, with the exceptions being filenames and long
names. It is this screen where you'll also be able to toggle which TYPES
of bases can use the taglists.

   You'll also be asked if you wish to go immediately to this screen upon
completion of a "Scanning Directory" operation. See @{"SCANDIR" link SCANDIR} for more
information on this.

   You may use CNet Ranges when specifying which lists you wish changed.
@endnode
@node GRABTAGS "Grab(Download) Taglines"
Command: Grab(Download) Taglines

   Pressing `G' will allow you to GRAB(or Download) one or more taglists.
You'll be asked if you wish SuperTags to use ZIP or LHA to create the
archive. You'll then be asked which protocol you wish to use and then
must, then and there, download the archive.

   If the system is set to recognize you as a CNet SysOp, you'll also be
given the INDEX(.ndx) file(s), in addition to the taglists, so that you
can then ADOPT them into your copies of SuperTags.
@endnode
@node INFO "Information on Tagline Lists"
Command: Information on Tagline Lists

   Pressing `I' will allow you to view Information about selected list(s).
This information includes how many tags the list contains, who can use the
tags, and whether or not MCI Color Commands are allowed in this list.
You'll also be shown some example tags from that listing.

   See the @{"GENERAL" link GENERAL} item for more information concerning selecting multiple
lists to view information on.
@endnode
@node FLAGS "Enable/Disable Text Type Flags"
Command: Flags

   Pressing `F' will allow you to adjust your TagLine flags pertaining to
the TYPES of messages you create. Presently, there are five flags you can
enable and/or disable:

Enable/Disable Tagging of Net-Mails

    - These are textual messages you create on the this bulletin board,
      but whose contents will be sent to some other location. This could
      be through a network like FIDO-Net or CLink or to one of the larger
      commercial services, like Compu-Serve or America On-Line.

Enable/Disable Tagging of E-Mails

   - These are textual messages you create specifically for one user on
     this bulletin board. This user will be the only one able to read your
     message, unless (s)he chooses to forward your message to someone else.

Enable/Disable Tagging of Feedbacks

   - These are textual messages you create specifically addressed to the
     SysOp of this bulletin board. Only the SysOp will be able to read
     these messages.

Enable/Disable Tagging of Posts

   - These are textual messages you create in the Public Message Areas(or
     Forums) located on this bbs. A post is a message meant to START a new
     topic of discussion, and may be read by all users who have access to
     this area on the bbs.

Enable/Disable Tagging of Responses

   - These are textual messages you create in REPLY to topics in the
     Public Message Areas(or Forums) located on this bbs. You generally
     use responses to ADD TO the ongoing discussion of a given topic.
     Again, all users who have access to this area of the bbs may read
     your responses.
@endnode
@node MAKEBORDER "Custom Border Creation"
Command: Custom Border Creation

   Pressing `B' will take you to the Custom Border screen. On this screen,
you can define the eight characters used to make the border:

  A                            B    C
   \\                           |   /
    .-- SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ----.
D - | This is an example tagline! | - E
    `-----------------------------'
   /               |               \\
  F                G                H

        A> upper left corner
        B> upper horizontal
        C> upper right corner
        D> left vertical
        E> right vertical
        F> lower left corner
        G> lower horizontal
        H> lower right corner

   Starting in v2.53 of SuperTags, you now have the ability to use the
8-bit IBM Graphic Characters in the creation of your custom border.
You'll initially be placed in TEXT mode, whereas whatever you type on the
keyboard will be used as the characters to make your border with. You can
use the ESCAPE key to switch between the different modes. When in an IBM
mode, the characters you type will produce the shown equivalent IBM
character graphics.

   You can then use either the "Custom" or "Random" method under the
@{"METHODS" link METHODS} item to use your newly customized border.

   In the 2-Line format, the `F' item(lower horizontal) is used to create
the lower border character. No frame is used in the 1-Line format. See
@{"FORMATS" link FORMATS} for more information.
@endnode
@node REBUILDLISTS "Rebuild Tagline Listings"
Command: Rebuild Tagline Listings

   In the event you ever manually add and/or change the contents of one or
more of the tagline data files, or if you suspect the validity of one of
the index files, REBUILDING may be to your advantage.

   This process is similar to scanning, except that you specify lists
which already exist in your TagLines file. The same steps will be
executed as are discussed under Scanning Directory, upon which the
index file will have been recreated for you. See the @{"SCANDIR" link SCANDIR} item for
more information.

   You can use CNet Ranges while selecting lists to rebuild.
@endnode
@node ARGUMENTS "Using TAGSM Command With Arguments"
Command: Using TAGSM Command With Arguments

   You can also use the following ARGUMENTS right after the TAGSM command
from the CNet prompt to activate other utilities:

   - Specify an ID Number to view that ID's _SuperTags Config file. This
     is helpful in locating problems a user might be having, while trying
     to use SuperTags.

      Example:    Main> tagsm 1     (Check ID # 1's  config)
                  Main> tagsm 32    (Check ID # 32's config)

      NOTE: This utility is ONLY available by use of the argument!

   - Specify an "M" to run the automaintenance file:

      Example:    Main> tagsm m     (Execute AMAINT module)

   - Specify an "A" to initiate an ADOPT operation on orphaned taglists:

      Example:    Main> tagsm a     (Adopt NEW Indexed Taglists)

   - Specify an "S" to initiate a "Scan Directory" operation, where ONLY
     files without INDEX files will be scanned:

      Example:    Main> tagsm s     (Scan for NEW Taglists)

   - Specify an "R" to initiate a "Scan Directory" operation on ALL files
     located in the TagData/ directory(Rebuild Operation):

      Example:    Main> tagsm r     (Rebuild Indexes for ALL Lists)

   - Specify a "?" to see a brief HELP Menu of available arguments:

      Example:    Main> tagsm ?     (List all available arguments)
@endnode
@node BORDERS "Border Types"
Command: Border Types

   This program allows you to place a border around the actual tagline
that will be appended to your text messages. This option allows you to
specify which border you wish to use:

   - Pick Random Border

      This option will randomly select one of the 13 border types listed
      below(including NO border).

   - Use No Border

      This option simply displays the "SuperTags" text and the tagline
      text, with NO border.

   - Shadowed IBM

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen
        This is an example tagline! Ü
       ßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßß

   - Single Line Ascii

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen --------.
      | This is an example tagline! |
      `-----------------------------'

   - Single Line IBM

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄż
      ł This is an example tagline! ł
      ŔÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄŮ

   - Double Line Ascii

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen =========
      = This is an example tagline! =
      ===============================

   - Double Line IBM

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ»
      ş This is an example tagline! ş
      ČÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍĽ

   - Narrow Box Ascii

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen _________
      | This is an example tagline! |
      ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   - Narrow Box IBM

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜ
      Ű This is an example tagline! Ű
      ßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßßß

   - Wide Box Ascii

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ~~~~~~~~|
      | This is an example tagline! |
      |_____________________________|

   - Wide Box IBM

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen ßßßßßßßßŰ
      Ű This is an example tagline! Ű
      ŰÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜÜŰ

   - Textured Ascii

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen #########
      # this is an example tagline! #
      ###############################

   - Textured IBM

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen °°°°°°°°°
      ° This is an example tagline! °
      °°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°°

   - Create Custom Border

      This option allows you to use the custom border you created(or the
      default custom border if you haven't created one yet). See the
      @{"MAKEBORDER" link MAKEBORDER} command for info on creating your own border. Here's
      what the default custom border looks like:

      SuperTags 2.53 Chosen --------\\
      | This is an example tagline! |
      \\-----------------------------/
@endnode
@node INTRO "Introduction to Taglines & SuperTags"
Command: Introduction to Taglines & SuperTags

    SuperTags is a program to hopefully make using taglines a bit easier,
as well as more fun!  A "tagline" is usually one line of text that follows
the message text you create in the editor.  This message text could be
anything from a personal mail message, feedback, public postings or
responses.

    This config program allows you to specify how you wish taglines to be
used by you.  Under most circumstances, a tagline IS appended to your
text messages SOMEHOW, but this program lets you specify EXACTLY how you
want them used.

    The other sections of this Help System will explain what the different
things you see on the config screen mean, and how they are used. If, after
you've read through the appropriate help areas, you are still confused,
please don't hesitate to ask your SysOp for further assistance...
@endnode
@node METHODS "Tagline Use Method"
Command: Tagline Use Method

   This refers to how you wish this program to do it's job. There are
presently ten ways this program can proceed:

   Disable SuperTags; Do NOT Append a Tag.

      - Using this method, you can effectivly DISABLE the use of taglines
        from ALL of your messages. This is sometimes helpful if you use an
        off-line reader to do the majority of your posting and responding.
        Your user signature will still be appended to the messages,
        however.

   Pick A Random List, then a Random Tag.

      - Using this method, you'll never be bothered by the program when a
        tagline is needed. It will simply select a tagline at random from
        one of the lists you have access to.

   Ask Me About Lists & Tags Each Time.

      - Using this method, you'll be asked to choose a list of tags each
        time you save a text message. You can then choose a tag from
        within that list, create one of your own, or switch to a different
        list, until you've found one you like.

   Pick a Random CHOSEN List, then a Random Tag.

      - Using this method, you can tell the program to select a random
        tagline from one of the lists you specified earlier. Refer to
        item number 4 for information concerning @{"Chosen Lists" link CHOSENLISTS}.

   Ask Me For CHOSEN List, then a Tag.

      - Using this method, you'll be asked to choose a list of tags from
        your CHOSEN listing. You can then choose a tag from within that
        list, create one of your own, or switch to a different list,
        until you've found one you like.

   Pick a Random CHOSEN Tag.

      - Using this method, you can tell the program to select a random
        tagline from a group of taglines you specified earlier. Refer to
        item number 5 for information concerning @{"Chosen Tags" link CHOSENTAGS}.

   Ask Me For A CHOSEN Tag.

      - Using this method, you'll be shown your listing of CHOSEN tags,
        where you can select to use one of those, create your own, or
        quit without adding a tag.

   Pick a Random CHOSEN List OR a Random CHOSEN Tag.

      - This method simply allows you to COMBINE the affects of the above
        two methods, where there will be a possibility that one of your
        CHOSEN tags is picked OR if a Random tag will be selected from
        one of your CHOSEN Lists.

   Load the SuperTags Config Each Time.

      - Using this method will allow you to use the SuperTags Config to
        change options after every time you save a text message. This is
        helpful, while first using this program, until you find the
        settings that work best for you.

   Use QuickTags from Selected Listing.

      - This mode allows you to specify "QuickTags" execution. When in
        QuickTags mode, you do NOT have the ability to customize any of
        the numerous different options pertaining to taglines in general.
        you are allowed to specify one tagline listing, from which tags
        will be sequentially chosen from. Tags in "QuickTags" mode are
        formatted for 1-Line, without using color of any kind. You should
        also make sure not to specify a tag list which may cont the
        FASTEST way of creating taglines for your messages, even if it's
        not quite as configurable as some of the above mentioned modes.
@endnode
@node NEXTPAST "The NEXT and PAST Tagline Lists"
Command: The NEXT and PAST Tagline Lists

   If you are using more than 60 tagline listings, they all can't fit on
the Maint Screen at one time, so a second screen will be created to hold
them.

   Using the `N'ext and `P'ast commands allow you to traverse through
these screens and see all the listings on file.
@endnode
@node TOGGLEBASES "Toggle Taglines/User Signatures/8-Bit Graphics in Bases"
Command: Toggle Taglines/User Signatures/8-Bit Graphics in Bases

   There are some subbases where you may wish to DISABLE the use of
TagLines, User Signatures, or 8-bit IBM Graphic characters, while at the
same time allowing them to be used in other subbases. TOGGLE SUBS allows
you to specify which subbases you wish to disable the use of any of these
in.

   Use the Arrow Keys to select the base you wish to Toggle, then press 
your ENTER key.  You can press `D' to DISABLE ALL bases within the SAME 
network and `E' to ENABLE ALL bases within the SAME network. Press `R' to 
RESTRICT ALL for ONE base, or `A' to ACTIVATE ALL for ONE base.

   To the left of each Yes/No data item, you MAY see a cyan colored 
checkmark. This denotes the currently set item on that base's EL screen 
within CNet proper as defined below:

     If next to the "Use Tags" column, it indicates that you have BOTH 
     "No Signatures" AND "Disable all MCI" set to YES on that base's EL 
     screen.

     If next to the "Use Sigs" column, it indicates that you have 
     "No Signatures" set to YES on that base's EL screen.

     If next to the "Use Gra." column, it indicates that you have 
     "Disable all MCI" set to YES on that base's EL screen.

NOTE: As you should have ALL your bases set to NOT use Signatures, so that 
      SuperTags can append them itself, you should see a checkmark next to 
      EVERY base in the "Use Sigs" column. If you see bases that do NOT 
      have checkmarks, you should go into those bases and use the EL command
      to disable signatures, else any messages posted within those bases 
      will have TWO signatures appended, one by CNet and another by 
      SuperTags!
@endnode
@node TITLES "Title Text Settings"
Command: Title Text Settings

   The `Title Text Setting' option allows you to choose the text that
will accompany your tagline in the final output. There are presently four
options:

    - Display NEITHER STags Title OR List Name.

        This setting will include NO extra text characters, besides those
        that make up the actual tagline(and any others needed to create
        the chosen border effect).

    - Display BOTH STags Title AND List Name.

        This setting will display the "SuperTags 2.53" (or "STags2.53" if
        in 1-Line format) text, along with the name of the listing the
        tagline was taken from. Note that in the 1-Line format, only ONE
        piece of info can be displayed, so if "Show BOTH" is chosen, only
        the Title text will be displayed.

    - Display ONLY the STags Title Text String.

        Only the "SuperTags 2.53" (or "STags2.53" if in 1-Line format) text
        string will be displayed when creating the tagline. The name of the
        list the tagline was taken from will NOT appear in the final output.

    - Display ONLY the List Name Text String.

        Only the NAME of the list the tagline was taken from will be
        displayed when creating the tagline. The title text will NOT appear
        in the final output. Note that this name will ALSO be used in the
        1- and 2-Line format modes as well(whereas it only apeared in the
        3-Line format in earlier versions).
@endnode
@node RANGES "Cnet's RANGES Help File!"
   Without specifying any particular item or range of items, the various
commands behave differently:

        Browse, Scan, Search:   All items
        Read, Yank:             New items
        all others:             Current, or most recently used item

   However, there are many additional ways provided in which to express
your needs to the system.  To specify which items you wish (where # is
an integer):

        #               any item number
        #-#             a RANGE of values
        ,               to separate multiple RANGES

   Other range specifying keywords include:

      new             brandnew items and new responses
      brandnew        entirely new items only
      newresp         old items with new responses
      free            items marked as no-charge downloads
      favorite        the sysop's favorites
      by {user}       items posted/uploaded by {user} (handle or acc#)
      byme            items posted/uploaded by you
      to {user}       items addressed to {user} (handle or acc#)
      tome            items addressed to you
      mess            read/scan messagess individually and in post order
      private         items marked as private
      reverse         move from highest to lowest item/message number
      since           messages AFTER date ; DAY[-MONTH][-YEAR][,HOUR]
      until           messages BEFORE date; DAY[-MONTH][-YEAR][,HOUR]
      'text'          items with 'text' found in the title or description
      unval           unvalidated, unfinished, or no description
      pass            skip the Respond or Pass? prompt
      all   (or *)
      first (or ^)
      last  (or $)
      this  (or . or current)
      next
      previous

Examples:

S FAVORITE              Look for the sysop's favorite items
D TOME                  Download the items addressed to you
R MESS TOME             Read items and responses addressed to you
@endnode
